        <p id="Courting_Cyndi_I_prepared_for_marriage_and_having_a_family_ear">

        <span id="textspand">Courting Cyndi<br /><br /></span><span id="textspand1">I prepared for marriage and having a family early in my youth. In our church, we’re taught we should be married in the temple, so that was my goal and it’s a goal I always had: receive the priesthood, serve a mission and get married in the temple. Examples of this pattern were all around me in my parents and relatives. Preparation happened in my home growing up during Family Home Evenings, family outings and other traditions. I also learned as a priesthood holder to treat women carefully and &nbsp;with respect.<br /><br />Through the process of serving a mission I think I gained a lot of confidence needed to be a worthy husband. I was not an active dater before my mission at all. Girls intimidated me and I just felt I needed to mature more. When I came home from my mission I began to date more frequently. I was attending Ricks College and probably dated four or five different girls the first semester. I met Cyndi the second semester. There were a couple other girls, but I wasn’t serious with any of them; it just never got to that point. But with Cyndi, we got along well and we were led to each other through several different avenues. <br /><br />One of those avenues was through a missionary companion of mine who knew Cyndi when she was 10 years old in Miskoge, Oklahoma. There was another link through a group of girls I grew up with in Rexburg that knew Cyndi and her friend Gina Parkinson. They recommended that Cyndi look me up and see if I would date her. She had another group of friends all from Texas that saw the same thing and thought we were pretty compatible. <br /></span>
        <!--iframe id="spotify" src="https://embed.spotify.com/?uri=spotify:track:1jFhnVoJkcB4lf9tT0rSZS" width="300" height="80" frameborder="0" allowtransparency="true"></iframe-->
        
        </p>
        <div id="nickelstoryBox" class="clearfix">
            <p id="_The_Nickel_On_one_of_our_first_dates_we_were_all_dressed_up">
            <span id="textspand2">The Nickel </span><span id="textspand3"><br /></span><span id="textspand4">Randy Bird</span>
            </p>
            <!--img id="soundcloudnickel" src="img/soundcloudnickel.png" class="image" /-->
            <p id="_The_Nickel_On_one_of_our_first_dates_we_were_all_dressed_up1">
            <span id="textspand5">On one of our first dates, we were all dressed up and over at Cyndi’s apartment. I think my friend Todd and I were waiting for her to be ready and when she came out we were just clowning back and forth a little bit. I remember Todd told a joke and we were laughing about it. Now I’m not a storyteller and I’m not a joke teller at all, as jokes just don’t stick in my mind. That’s why this story is a little out of character for me. <br /><br />It started with me saying to Cyndi, I bet you a nickel I can kiss you without touching you. And she said, No you can’t. So I said, Yes I can. And she just turned to her girlfriends and said, That’s just not possible. How do you kiss someone without touching them? I told her again, I can do it. She stood up to me to let me try, so I just kissed her right on the lips and said, Here’s your nickel. Sorry I lost the bet. Her mouth fell wide open as she did not count on me wanting to lose the bet. She was totally baffled, turned all colors and shades of red and couldn’t believe she’d been snookered into that little trick. It’s one of our good stories. <br /><br />The story about the nickel is out of character because I’m actually a slow mover. I didn’t formally kiss Cyndi until we’d been dating three months -- I’m talking about the doorstep kiss, where you bring her home and kiss goodbye. After two months of steady dating, I was still saying goodbye at the door and then I’d just turn and leave. So it was not like me to have a story like this. But it’s fun to tell years later.</span>
            </p>
        </div>
