        <p id="Looking_from_the_outside_I_don’t_know_if_you_can_judge_whether">
        Looking from the outside, I don’t know if you can judge whether people are compatible or not, but after one date, I knew that we were. It started out well because she liked basketball, which was one of my passions. We went to a basketball game on one of our first dates and if she didn’t like basketball, I don't think it would have worked out. If she had put her foot down and said, “No, I don’t like games,” I think that would have been the end of it, haha. But she was willing and genuinely liked being with me and I genuinely liked being with her. We ended up dating for about four months, but it was a slow process. I am not a fast mover and my personality is not a take-charge, head-forward type of personality. Put it this way: I grew up in a family with three older brothers who were pretty dominant, so being younger I was just complacent to just watch and see how things turned out and to move with the flow as they went. As long as I felt they were going in a good direction, I would keep pursuing it. So with Cyndi, it just kept growing. <br /> <br />

        It was easy to see that if I just stayed on this path and we just kept doing different things together, we’d definitely fall in love with each other. We found we were compatible in all sorts of different situations. Through the process of two to three months, we dated frequently; probably near the end there in March and April, we saw each other on a daily basis. I made sure we did through one circumstance or another. So it was not love at first sight, but she certainly had the personality that I liked. She was very much like my mother. She was respectful and the word I used when I was dating her was "vivacious!" To me that’s what she was and I enjoyed that. She always had a spark and she was always fun to be with. So after a period of time, it was obvious I was going to pursue this as far as it goes and hopefully she felt the same way.

